{"title_page": "Liang Teck Meng", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n{{Chinese name|[[Liang (surname)|Liang (\u6881)]]}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay titles#Honorary style|Yang Berbahagia]] [[Malay titles#Federal titles|Datuk]]\n| name = Liang Teck Meng\n| honorific-suffix  = {{small|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Malaysia|PJN]]}}\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6881\u5fb7\u660e}}}}\n| image = Datuk liang profile photo.jpg\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|07|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Johor]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office1 = [[Secretary-General]] of [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Movement Party]]\n| term_start1 = 2013\n| term_end1 = 2018\n| 1blankname1 = President\n| 1namedata1 = [[Mah Siew Keong]]\n| predecessor1 = Mah Siew Keong ''(Acting)''\n| successor1 = Mak Kah Keong\n| constituency_MP = [[Simpang Renggam (federal constituency)|Simpang Renggam]], Johor\n| parliament = Malaysian\n| term_start       = 8 March 2008\n| term_end         = 9 May 2018\n| predecessor      = Kerk Choo Ting ([[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor        = [[Maszlee Malik]] ([[Malaysian United Indigenous Party|PPBM]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| majority = 7,853 [[2008 Malaysian general election|(2008)]]<br/> 5,706 [[2013 Malaysian general election|(2013)]]\n| party = [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|GERAKAN]]\n| otherparty = [[Barisan Nasional|Barisan Nasional (BN)]] (until 2018)\n| profession = Engineer\n| occupation = Politician\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = 2 sons\n| alma_mater = [[Tohoku University]]\n| website =\n| footnotes = {{facebook|liangteckmeng}}\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Federal titles|Datuk]] '''Liang Teck Meng''' ({{zh|t=|s=\u6881\u5fb7\u660e|p=Li\u00e1ng D\u00e9 M\u00edng}}; born 24 July 1971) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician and was the [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[Simpang Renggam (federal constituency)|Simpang Renggam]] constituency in the [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|State]] of [[Johor]] (2008 - 2018). He was Secretary General for the [[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia]] (GERAKAN), previously a component party in the [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition (2013 - 2018).\n\n==Education and personal life==\nLiang Teck Meng obtain his secondary education from [[Foon Yew High School]] (1984 to 1989). He received a distinction in his [[Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia|SPM]] and after that he went to the Federal Institute of Technology to study Electrical Engineering (1989 to 1992). Later, he went to study at the Japanese language from the prestigious Asia Student Cultural Association<ref>ASCA.[http://www.abk.or.jp/e/ \"Official Website\"]. Retrieved on 19 April 2013.</ref> He later went to the [[Tohoku University]], [[Sendai]], Japan to continue in the field of Electrical Engineering.\n\nLiang is an engineer by profession, and is married with two sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=/2008/3/27/lifefocus/20726272&sec=lifefocus|title=Trombone player|date=27 March 2008|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications (Malaysia)|accessdate=30 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604032405/http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F27%2Flifefocus%2F20726272&sec=lifefocus|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nLiang was elected to federal Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 election]], succeeding fellow Gerakan member Kerk Choo Ting in the seat of [[Simpang Renggam (federal constituency)|Simpang Renggam]].<ref name=\"The Star:2008 GE results\">{{Cite web\n |title=Malaysia Decides 2008 \n |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)]] \n |url=http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409212729/http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-date= 9 April 2008 \n |accessdate=30 January 2010 \n}} Percentage figures are calculated based on total turnout. Includes results from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=/2008/2/22/election2008/20408582&sec=Election2008|title=Two in running for CM's post in Penang|last=Shari|first=Izatun|author2=Goh, Kelvin|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications (Malaysia)|accessdate=30 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604032353/http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F2%2F22%2Felection2008%2F20408582&sec=Election2008|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Liang's victory was one of only two for Gerakan in the 12 federal seats it contested.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/southeastasia/view/334104/1/.html|title=Malaysia's Gerakan Party rejects Koh Tsu Koon's resignation offer|date=11 March 2008|work=channelnewsasia.com|publisher=MediaCorp|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> He was reelected to Parliament in the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]] as the only successful GERAKAN candidate, and remained the only Gerakan MP until [[Mah Siew Keong]] won the [[2014 Telok Intan by-election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/mah-teluk-intan-victory-proves-gerakan-still-strong|title=Mah: Teluk Intan victory proves Gerakan still strong|date=1 June 2014|work=The Malay Mail|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> However Liang have lost in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 election]]. 23 June 2018, Liang, Mah Siew Keong and among all leaders have unanimously decided GERAKAN to officially withdraw from BN and now independent party as opposition.\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P151 [[Simpang Renggam (federal constituency)|Simpang Renggam]], Johor<ref name=\"The Star:2008 GE results\"/><ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web  | title = Malaysia General Election   | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]  | url = http://undi.info/#  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name =\"myundi pru 13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |title=my undi : Kawasan & Calon-Calon PRU13 : Keputusan PRU13 (Archived copy) |website=www.myundi.com.my|accessdate=2014-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331000718/http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |archivedate=31 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Utusan PRU 13 results\">{{cite web|url=http://ww2.utusan.com.my/utusan/special.asp?pr=PilihanRaya2013&pg=keputusan.htm|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum ke-13|work=[[Utusan Malaysia]]|accessdate=26 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321134049/http://ww2.utusan.com.my/utusan/special.asp?pr=PilihanRaya2013&pg=keputusan.htm|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=