{"title_page": "William Leong", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Liang (surname)|Leong (\u6881)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n| name = William Leong\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6881\u81ea\u575a}}}}\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| image =\n| caption =\n| office = Chair of the [[Major Public Appointments Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 4 December 2018\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = ''Office established''\n| successor = \n| constituency_MP1 = [[Selayang (federal constituency)|Selayang]]\n| parliament1 = Malaysian\n| term_start1 = 8 March 2008\n| term_end1 =\n| majority1 = 3,567 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />17,846 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />40,657 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor1 = [[Chan Kong Choy]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]] \u2013 [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor1 =\n| birth_name = William Leong Jee Keen\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|01|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ipoh]], [[Perak]], [[Federation of Malaya]] {{small|(now [[Malaysia]])}}\n| residence = [[Klang Valley]], [[Malaysia]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| party = [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR) {{small|(2008-2015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015-present)}}\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| profession = [[Lawyer]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = 3\n| website = {{url|http://williamleongjeekeen.blogspot.com}}\n| footnotes = {{pom|3620}}\n| signature = William Leong signature.png\n}}\n\n'''William Leong Jee Keen''' ({{zh|t=\u6881\u81ea\u5805|s=\u6881\u81ea\u575a|p=Li\u00e1ng Z\u00ecji\u0101n}}; born 27 January 1957) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for [[Selayang (federal constituency)|Selayang]] constituency in [[Selangor]]. He is a member of the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) in the ruling [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition.\n\nOn 4 December 2018, Leong was elected chair of the [[Major Public Appointments Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLeong is also a lawyer,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2008/03/11/capable-individuals-will-be-picked-for-the-job/|title=Capable individuals will be picked for the job|date=11 March 2008|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> and has three children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=/2008/3/3/election2008/20509580&sec=Election2008|title=The hard road to success|date=3 March 2008|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=11 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLeong was elected to Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], winning the seat of Selayang from the ruling [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition.<ref name=\"election results\">{{Cite web|title = Malaysia Decides 2008|work =|publisher = [[The Star (Malaysia)]]|date =|url = http://thestar.com.my/election/|format =| doi =| accessdate = 11 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P97 {{pseat|Selayang}}, Selangor<ref name=\"election results\"/><ref name=\"SPR election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''30,701'''\n|rowspan=2|'''51.67%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Lee Li Yew ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |27,134\n|45.67%\n|rowspan=2|60,920\n|rowspan=2|3,567\n|rowspan=2|76.57%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/red}} |\n|Koh Swe Yong ([[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|PRM]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,332\n|2.24%\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''52,287'''\n|rowspan=2|'''57.40%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Donald Lim Siang Chai ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |34,441\n|37.81%\n|rowspan=2|92,528\n|rowspan=2|17,846\n|rowspan=2|87.38%\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: #29AB87;\" |\n|Mohd Hazizi Abdul Rahman ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Front|BERJASA]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,152\n|4.56%\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''60,158'''\n|rowspan=2|'''61.38%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Kang Meng Fuat ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |19,501\n|19.90%\n|rowspan=2|99,450\n|rowspan=2|40,657\n|rowspan=2|85.60%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Hashim Abd Karim ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |18,343\n|18.72%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Major Public Appointments Select Committee]]\n*[[Selayang (federal constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Selangor-FedRep}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leong, William}}\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:People from Perak]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Liang (surname)|Leong (\u6881)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n| name = William Leong\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6881\u81ea\u575a}}}}\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| image =\n| caption =\n| office = Chair of the [[Major Public Appointments Select Committee]]\n| term_start = 4 December 2018\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = ''Office established''\n| successor = \n| constituency_MP1 = [[Selayang (federal constituency)|Selayang]]\n| parliament1 = Malaysian\n| term_start1 = 8 March 2008\n| term_end1 =\n| majority1 = 3,567 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />17,846 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />40,657 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor1 = [[Chan Kong Choy]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]] \u2013 [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor1 =\n| birth_name = William Leong Jee Keen\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|01|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ipoh]], [[Perak]], [[Federation of Malaya]] {{small|(now [[Malaysia]])}}\n| residence = [[Klang Valley]], [[Malaysia]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| party = [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR) {{small|(2008-2015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015-present)}}\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| profession = [[Lawyer]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = 3\n| website = {{url|http://williamleongjeekeen.blogspot.com}}\n| footnotes = {{pom|3620}}\n| signature = William Leong signature.png\n}}\n\n'''William Leong Jee Keen''' ({{zh|t=\u6881\u81ea\u5805|s=\u6881\u81ea\u575a|p=Li\u00e1ng Z\u00ecji\u0101n}}; born 27 January 1957) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for [[Selayang (federal constituency)|Selayang]] constituency in [[Selangor]]. He is a member of the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) in the ruling [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition.\n\nOn 4 December 2018, Leong was elected chair of the [[Major Public Appointments Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLeong is also a lawyer,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2008/03/11/capable-individuals-will-be-picked-for-the-job/|title=Capable individuals will be picked for the job|date=11 March 2008|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> and has three children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=/2008/3/3/election2008/20509580&sec=Election2008|title=The hard road to success|date=3 March 2008|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=11 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLeong was elected to Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], winning the seat of Selayang from the ruling [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition.<ref name=\"election results\">{{Cite web|title = Malaysia Decides 2008|work =|publisher = [[The Star (Malaysia)]]|date =|url = http://thestar.com.my/election/|format =| doi =| accessdate = 11 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P97 {{pseat|Selayang}}, Selangor<ref name=\"election results\"/><ref name=\"SPR election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''30,701'''\n|rowspan=2|'''51.67%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Lee Li Yew ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |27,134\n|45.67%\n|rowspan=2|60,920\n|rowspan=2|3,567\n|rowspan=2|76.57%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/red}} |\n|Koh Swe Yong ([[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|PRM]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,332\n|2.24%\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''52,287'''\n|rowspan=2|'''57.40%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Donald Lim Siang Chai ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |34,441\n|37.81%\n|rowspan=2|92,528\n|rowspan=2|17,846\n|rowspan=2|87.38%\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: #29AB87;\" |\n|Mohd Hazizi Abdul Rahman ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Front|BERJASA]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,152\n|4.56%\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''William Leong Jee Keen'''}} ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|rowspan=2 align=\"right\" |'''60,158'''\n|rowspan=2|'''61.38%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Kang Meng Fuat ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |19,501\n|19.90%\n|rowspan=2|99,450\n|rowspan=2|40,657\n|rowspan=2|85.60%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Hashim Abd Karim ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" 