]])\n|align=\"right\" |'''28,287'''\t\n|'''85.42%'''\n|{{Party shading/S46}} |\n|{{nowrap|Amin Hussaini Abd Manan}} ([[Semangat 46|S46]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,827\n|14.58%\n|11,884\n|23,460\n|70.88%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]'''<ref name=\"election results\"/>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|-\n|[[1997 Permatang by-election|1997]]\n|N10 [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]], P89 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''9,590'''\t\n|'''84.12%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Mohd Maskuri Mardzuki}} ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,810\n|15.88%\n|11,884\n|7,780\n|64.18%\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|N10 [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]], P89 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''8,621'''\t\n|'''60.35%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|Mohd Yahya Mat Sahri}} ([[Keadilan|KeADILan]])\n|align=\"right\" |5,665\n|39.65%\n|14,755\n|2,956\n|73.72%\n|}\n\n==Honour==\n===Honours of Malaysia===\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2004)<ref name=IST>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Selangor}} :\n** [[File:MY-SEL Order of the Crown of Selangor - Knight Grand Commander - SPMS.svg|50px]] Knight Grand Commander of the [[Order of the Crown of Selangor]] (SPMS) - '''Dato' Seri''' (1988)<ref name=IST/>\n* {{Flag|Federal Territory (Malaysia)}} :\n** [[File:MY-FED Darjah Mahkota Wilayah - Grand Knight - SUMW.svg|50px]] Grand Knight of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|Order of the Territorial Crown]] (SUMW) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2012)<ref name=IST/>\n\n==Death==\nAbu Hassan died of a [[cardiac arrest]] on 8 September 2018 at 8.05pm at the [[Columbia Asia|Columbia Asia Hospital]], Bukit Rimau, at age 77.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/409726/former-selangor-mb-abu-hassan-omar-dies|title=Former Selangor MB Abu Hassan Omar dies|date=8 September 2018|publisher=[[New Strait Times]]| accessdate = 9 September 2018 }}</ref> Abu Hassan's remains was brought to his residence at Kota Kemuning, Shah Alam before brought to the [[Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah Mosque]], Shah Alam for prayers and then burial at [[Shah Alam Royal Mausoleum]], [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]] on the next day.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | author= Ruwaida Md Zain | title=Abu Hassan akan dikebumikan di Makam Diraja Shah Alam | date=9 September 2018 | publisher=[[Berita Harian]] | url= https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2018/09/471543/abu-hassan-akan-dikebumikan-di-makam-diraja-shah-alam | work =| pages = | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | language =Malay }}</ref> Sultan Selangor, [[Sharafuddin of Selangor|Sultan Sharafuddin Idris Shah]] dan Tengku Permaisuri Selangor, Tengku Permaisuri Norashikin attended the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | author= | title=Jenazah Abu Hassan Omar selamat dikebumikan | date=9 September 2018 | publisher=[[Astro Awani]] | url= http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/jenazah-abu-hassan-omar-selamat-dikebumikan-185162 | work =| pages = | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | language =Malay }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muhammad Muhammad Taib]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chief Ministers of Selangor|Chief Minister of Selangor]]|years=6 June 1997 \u2013 9 August 2000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Khir Toyo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Third Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Fourth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Fifth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Selangor]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Members of the Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Selangor state executive councillors]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Selangor]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Malay name|Abu Hassan|Omar}}\n{{Infobox President\n| honorific-prefix   = [[Malay styles and titles|Yang Berbahagia Tan Sri Dato' Seri]] [[Honorary Doctorate|(Dr.)]] [[Hajji|Haji]] \n| name          = Abu Hassan Omar\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia|PSM]] [[Order of the Crown of Selangor|SPMS]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|SUMW]]}}\n| image         = \n| image_size    = 150px\n| caption       =\n| order         = 12th [[List of Menteris Besar of Selangor|Menteri Besar of Selangor]]\n| monarch       = [[Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah|Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah]]\n| term_start    = 6 June 1997 \n| term_end      = 9 August 2000\n| predecessor   = [[Muhammad Muhammad Taib]]\n| successor     = [[Khir Toyo]]\n| office2       =\n| term_start2   = 8 July 1978\n| term_end2     = 30 April 1997\n| predecessor2  = Raja Nasron Raja Ishak  \n| successor2    = Jamaluddin Adnan \n| majority2     = 13,008 ([[1978 Malaysian general election|1978]])<br />18,299 ([[1982 Malaysian general election|1982]])<br />12,676 ([[1986 Malaysian general election|1986]])<br />9,456 ([[1990 Malaysian general election|1990]])<br />23,460 ([[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]])\n| parliament2   = Malaysian\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]]\n| office3       =\n| term_start3   = 29 May 1997\n| term_end3     = 9 August 2000\n| predecessor3  = Jamaluddin Adnan \n| successor3    = Abdul Aziz Mohd Noh\n| constituency_AM3 = [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]]\n| assembly3     = Selangor State\n| majority3     = 7,780 ([[1997 Permatang by-election|1997]])<br />2,956 ([[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]])\n| office4       =\n| term_start4   = \n| term_end4     = \n| predecessor4  = \n| successor4    = \n| constituency_AM4 = \n| assembly4     = \n| majority4     = \n| birth_name    = Abu Hassan bin Omar\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1940|09|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kuala Selangor District|Kuala Selangor]], [[Selangor]], [[Federated Malay States]]<br />(now [[Malaysia]])\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2018|09|08|1940|09|15|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]], Malaysia\n| resting_place = [[Shah Alam Royal Mausoleum]]\n| citizenship      = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| spouse        =  Wan Nor Daud\n| relations        =\n| children         = 5\n| residence     = Kota Kemuning, [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]], [[Malaysia]]\n| party         = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) \n| otherparty       = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Hull]]\n| occupation       = Administration and Diplomatic Officer (ADO), politician\n| profession       =\n| website          = \n| footnotes        =\n| signature =\n}}\n'''Abu Hassan bin Omar''' (15 September 1940 &ndash; 8 September 2018) was a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician from [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO), a major component party of [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition.<ref name=\"resignation\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-63991089/have-resigned-safeguard-my.html|title=I Have Resigned to Safeguard My Health - Abu Hassan|date=10 August 2000|work=The Malaysian National News Agency|publisher=Access My Library|accessdate=1 January 2010|location=Bernama}}</ref> He was the 12th [[Menteri Besar]] (Chief Minister) of [[Selangor]], [[Malaysia]],<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-64078431/abu-hassan-why-resigned.html|title=Abu Hassan: Why I resigned|date=11 August 2000|work=New Straits Times|accessdate=1 January 2010|location=DATUK}}</ref> from 1997 to 2000. Previously he was also the [[Minister of Women, Family and Community Development (Malaysia)|Minister of Social Welfare]] (1985\u20131986), [[Ministry of Federal Territories (Malaysia)|Minister of Federal Territories]] (1986\u20131987), [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] (1987\u20131991) and [[Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]] (1991\u20131997).  He was also a former [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] for [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]] (1978\u20131997) and [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly|Selangor state assemblyman]] for [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]] (1997\u20131999) in [[Selangor]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbu Hassan was born on 15 September 1940 in Bukit Belimbing, [[Kuala Selangor]], Selangor. He received his early education at the Malay School of Bukit Belimbing (1946\u20131950) before furthering his studies at [[Klang High School]] (1951\u20131957), [[Malay College Kuala Kangsar]] (1958\u20131959) and [[University of Hull]], England (1960\u20131963 and 1971\u20131973).<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite  web|url=http://www.selangor.gov.my/main.php?Content=vertsectiondetails&VsItemID=172&VertSectionID=5&CurLocation=44&Page=1 |title=Sejarah Menteri Besar : Mantan Dato\u2019 Menteri Besar Selangor|year=2008 |publisher=Laman Web Rasmi Kerajaan Negeri Selangor |language=Malay |accessdate=1 January 2010 |location=Selangor |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604140503/http://www.selangor.gov.my/main.php?Content=vertsectiondetails&VsItemID=172&VertSectionID=5&CurLocation=44&Page=1 |archivedate=4 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Abu Hassan was married to Wan Nor Daud and the couple had five children.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bharian.com.my/node/24277|title=Anak bekas MB Selangor meninggal dunia|date=20 December 2014|work=[[Bernama]]|language=Malay|publisher=[[Berita Harian]]|accessdate=22 September 2017|location=}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering politics, he served as Administration and Diplomatic Officer (ADO) from 1964 to 1978. He previously served as Chief Assistant Secretary of Economy Planning Unit in the Prime Minister's department, Assistant Secretary of Selangor State Government and Assistant Secretary of the Land and Federal Territory Development Ministry.<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n==Political career==\nAbu Hassan started his political career when he contested and won the [[Kuala Selangor]] parliamentary seat in the [[1978 Malaysian general election|1978 general election]] on 8 July 1978.<ref name=\"bio\"/> He successfully retained the seat in the subsequent [[1982 Malaysian general election|1982]], [[1986 Malaysian general election|1986]], [[1990 Malaysian general election|1990]] and [[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]] general elections.<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> In government, he was also the [[Minister of Women, Family and Community Development (Malaysia)|Minister of Social Welfare]] (1985\u20131986), [[Ministry of Federal Territories (Malaysia)|Minister of Federal Territories]] (1986\u20131987), [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] (1987\u20131991) and [[Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]] (1991\u20131997).<ref>{{cite news |title=Former Selangor MB Abu Hassan Omar passes away|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/08/abu-hassan-omar-passes-away/ |accessdate=10 September 2018 |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 1997, he resigned as [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] for Kuala Selangor and his cabinet minister post in order to contest the Selangor state seat of [[1997 Permatang by-election|Permatang by-election]] which fell vacant when its incumbent assemblyman, Jamaluddin Adnan also resigned. This arranged position swap occurred to enable him to be appointed the new Selangor Menteri Besar, to replace [[Muhammad Muhammad Taib]] who stepped down over currency irregularities court charges and controversies.<ref>{{cite news |title=By-election has been held before to bring in a new MB |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/01/28/byelection-has-been-held-before-to-bring-in-a-new-mb/ |last1= |first1= |work= The Star |date=28 Jan 2014 |publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Menteri Besar of Selangor===\nAfter being elected as a representative of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] in the by-election on 29 May 1997, he was appointed as the Menteri Besar of Selangor from 6 June 1997 to 9 August 2000.<ref name=\"bio\"/> There was controversy over the RM5 million expenditure to renovate the official residence of the Menteri Besar at Bukit Megawati, Shah Alam for Abu Hassan during his tenure.<ref name=\"resign\">{{cite news|url=http://ww1.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2000&dt=0811&pub=utusan_malaysia&sec=Muka_Hadapan&pg=fp_01.htm |title=Saya difitnah - Abu Hassan -- Ada pihak tohmah beliau punyai anak luar nikah dengan adik ipar |date=11 August 2000|work=Zaini Hassan, Amir Sarifuddin dan Radhuan Hassan|language=Malay|publisher=[[Berita Harian]]|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ugly\">{{cite news|url=http://malaysiansmustknowthetruth.blogspot.my/2011/05/ugly-malaysian-abu-hassan-omar.html#!/tcmbck |title=The Ugly Malaysian: Abu Hassan Omar |date=17 May 2011|work=|author=Hussein Abdul Hamid|language=|publisher=malaysiansmustknowthetruth.blogspot|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, a [[poison pen letter]] started circulating about an alleged sex scandal and ill-concealed relationship between Abu Hassan with his wife's sister. Abu Hassan had denied any wrongdoing, claiming his sister-in-law actually had married his good friend, a Chinese new [[Muallaf|Muslim convert]] (Muallaf) who coincidentally shared his Islamic name; Abu Hassan Tan Abdullah. He stated that as the reason their son's name was Mohamad Hafiz bin Abu Hassan, which had caused all the confusion.<ref name=\"resign\"/><ref name=\"ugly\"/> The opposition had reported the case to the Selangor Islamic Religious Department (JAIS) demanding an investigation into their relationship and if they have an illegitimate son under religious law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tranungkite.net/lama/berita9/harakah74.htm |title=Kes Abu Hassan Omar dilaporkan kepada Jais secara rasmi |last1= |first1= |author=Mat Zahari Ali |work=[[Harakah|Harakah Daily]]  |language=Malay |date=5 September 2000 |publisher=Tranung Kite |accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2000, Abu Hassan abruptly announced his resignation as Menteri Besar of Selangor citing health and family reasons but did not elaborate on other existing controversies and crisis bothering him.<ref name=\"resign\"/><ref name=\"ugly\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tranungkite.net/lama/berita8/pillai55.htm |title=And So A Menteri Besar Is Forced To Resign  |last1= |first1=  |work=[[M.G.G. Pillai]] |language=|date=|publisher=Tranung Kite |accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"election results\"/>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[1978 Malaysian general election|1978]]\n| rowspan=4|[[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n| rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\"|'''16,598'''\t\n| rowspan=2|'''70.80%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Norhadi Hasan Ali}} ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |3,590\n|15.31%\n| rowspan=2|N/A\n| rowspan=2|13,008\n| rowspan=2|N/A\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n| Supian Sirman ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| align=\"right\" | 3,257\n| 13.89%\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[1982 Malaysian general election|1982]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n| rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\"|'''21,409'''\t\n| rowspan=2|'''79.40%'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|Abd Rashid Daud}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n|align=\"right\" |3,110\n|11.53%\n| rowspan=2|28,013\n| rowspan=2|18,299\n| rowspan=2|74.54%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Sayan Marbin ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| align=\"right\" | 2,444\n| 9.06%\n|-\n|[[1986 Malaysian general election|1986]]\n|rowspan=2|P85 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''17,523'''\t\n|'''78.33%'''\n|{{Party shading/red}} |\n|{{nowrap|Zainudin Muhammad}} ([[Malaysian Nationalist Party|NASMA]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,847\n|21.67%\n|23,469\n|12,676\n|72.19%\n|-\n|[[1990 Malaysian general election|1990]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''17,964'''\t\n|'''67.86%'''\n|{{Party shading/S46}} |\n|{{nowrap|Mohamed Haniffa}} <br />([[Semangat 46|S46]])\n|align=\"right\" |8,508\n|32.14%\n|27,527\n|9,456\n|75.02%\n|-\n|[[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]]\n|P89 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]], [[Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''28,287'''\t\n|'''85.42%'''\n|{{Party shading/S46}} |\n|{{nowrap|Amin Hussaini Abd Manan}} ([[Semangat 46|S46]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,827\n|14.58%\n|11,884\n|23,460\n|70.88%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]'''<ref name=\"election results\"/>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|-\n|[[1997 Permatang by-election|1997]]\n|N10 [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]], P89 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''9,590'''\t\n|'''84.12%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Mohd Maskuri Mardzuki}} ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,810\n|15.88%\n|11,884\n|7,780\n|64.18%\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|N10 [[Permatang (state constituency)|Permatang]], P89 [[Kuala Selangor (federal constituency)|Kuala Selangor]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abu Hassan Omar'''}} ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''8,621'''\t\n|'''60.35%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|Mohd Yahya Mat Sahri}} ([[Keadilan|KeADILan]])\n|align=\"right\" |5,665\n|39.65%\n|14,755\n|2,956\n|73.72%\n|}\n\n==Honour==\n===Honours of Malaysia===\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2004)<ref name=IST>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Selangor}} :\n** [[File:MY-SEL Order of the Crown of Selangor - Knight Grand Commander - SPMS.svg|50px]] Knight Grand Commander of the [[Order of the Crown of Selangor]] (SPMS) - '''Dato' Seri''' (1988)<ref name=IST>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Federal Territory (Malaysia)}} :\n** [[File:MY-FED Darjah Mahkota Wilayah - Grand Knight - SUMW.svg|50px]] Grand Knight of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|Order of the Territorial Crown]] (SUMW) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2012)<ref name=IST>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAbu Hassan died of a [[cardiac arrest]] on 8 September 2018 at 8.05pm at the [[Columbia Asia|Columbia Asia Hospital]], Bukit Rimau, at age 77.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/409726/former-selangor-mb-abu-hassan-omar-dies|title=Former Selangor MB Abu Hassan Omar dies|date=8 September 2018|publisher=[[New Strait Times]]| accessdate = 9 September 2018 }}</ref> Abu Hassan's remains was brought to his residence at Kota Kemuning, Shah Alam before brought to the [[Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz Shah Mosque]], Shah Alam for prayers and then burial at [[Shah Alam Royal Mausoleum]], [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]] on the next day.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | author= Ruwaida Md Zain | title=Abu Hassan akan dikebumikan di Makam Diraja Shah Alam | date=9 September 2018 | publisher=[[Berita Harian]] | url= https://www.bharian.com.my/berita/nasional/2018/09/471543/abu-hassan-akan-dikebumikan-di-makam-diraja-shah-alam | work =| pages = | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | language =Malay }}</ref> Sultan Selangor, [[Sharafuddin of Selangor|Sultan Sharafuddin Idris Shah]] dan Tengku Permaisuri Selangor, Tengku Permaisuri Norashikin attended the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | author= | title=Jenazah Abu Hassan Omar selamat dikebumikan | date=9 September 2018 | publisher=[[Astro Awani]] | url= http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/jenazah-abu-hassan-omar-selamat-dikebumikan-185162 | work =| pages = | accessdate = 9 September 2018 | language =Malay }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muhammad Muhammad Taib]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chief Ministers of Selangor|Chief Minister of Selangor]]|years=6 June 1997 \u2013 9 August 2000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Khir Toyo]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Third Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Fourth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Fifth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Selangor]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Members of the Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Selangor state executive councillors]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Selangor]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abu_Hassan_Omar"}
{"title_page": "Saifuddin Abdullah", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Malay name|Saifuddin|Abdullah}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']]\n| name = Saifuddin Abdullah\n| native_name = \u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|DSAP]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Perak|DPMP]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]}}\n| image = Secretary Pompeo Meets with Malaysian FM Saifuddin Abdullah (42012332590) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Abdullah in 2018\n| birth_name = Saifuddin bin Abdullah\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|01|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Kampung Sungai Ara, [[Mentakab]], [[Pahang]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = [[Minister of Communications and Multimedia (Malaysia)|Minister of Communications and Multimedia]]\n| term_start = 10 March 2020\n| term_end = \n| primeminister = [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]\n| deputy = [[Zahidi Zainul Abidin]]\n| predecessor = [[Gobind Singh Deo]]\n| successor   = \n| constituency = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| monarch = [[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| office4 = Chief Secretary of [[Pakatan Harapan]]\n| 1blankname4 = Chairman\n| 1namedata4 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| leader4 = [[Anwar Ibrahim]]\n| president4 = [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]]\n| term_start4 = 19 October 2015\n| term_end4 = 24 February 2020\n| predecessor4 = ''Position established''\n| successor4  = [[Saifuddin Nasution Ismail]]\n| constituency4 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| office1 = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start1 = 2 July 2018\n| term_end1 = 24 February 2020\n| primeminister1 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| deputy1 = [[Marzuki Yahya]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Anifah Aman]]\n| successor1   = [[Hishammuddin Hussein]]\n| constituency1 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| monarch1 = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Higher Education II]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Najib Razak]]\n| alongside2 = [[Hou Kok Chung]]\n| minister2 = [[Mohamed Khaled Nordin]]\n| constituency2 = [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Idris Haron]]\n| successor2 = [[Mary Yap Kain Ching]] {{small|as Deputy Minister of Education}} \n| monarch2 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]\n| term_start2 = 10 April 2009\n| term_end2 = 15 May 2013\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Entrepreneur and Co-operatives Development]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| minister3 = [[Noh Omar]]\n| constituency3 = Temerloh\n| predecessor3 = Khamsiyah Yeop\n| successor3 = [[Tan Lian Hoe]] {{small|as Deputy Minister of Domestic Trade, Co-operatives and Consumerism}}\n| monarch3 = Mizan Zainal Abidin\n| term_start3 = 19 March 2008\n| term_end3 = 9 April 2009\n| term_start5 = 9 May 2018\n| term_end5 =\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| parliament5 = Malaysian\n| majority5 = 10,950 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor5 = [[Fauzi Abdul Rahman]] ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n| successor5 =\n| constituency_MP6 = [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]]\n| parliament6 = Malaysian\n| term_start6 = 8 March 2008\n| term_end6 = 5 May 2013\n| majority6 = 2,441 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])\n| predecessor6 = Mohd Sarit Yusoh ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]]) \n| successor6 = Nasrudin Hassan ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| party = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) {{small|(until 2015)}}<br />[[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2015-2020)}} <br/>[[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] (PPBM) (since 2020)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations =\n| spouse = Datin Norlin Shamsul Bahri\n| children = 1\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.saifuddinabdullah.com.my/}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']] '''Saifuddin bin Abdullah''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647; born 27 January 1961) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and [[Minister of Communications and Multimedia (Malaysia)|Minister of Communications and Multimedia]] and the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]. He is also a member of the ruling [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition. Previously, he was the Member of [[Parliament of Malaysia]] for the [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]] constituency in [[Pahang]] from 2008 to 2013 representing [[United Malay National Organisation]] (UMNO), the leading party in the then-ruling coalition of [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN).\n\n==Personal life==\nSaifuddin was born to an [[Ustad|ustaz]] father and a schoolteacher mother in [[Temerloh]] near [[Mentakab]], Pahang.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | author1 = Interview by Abdul Qayyum Jumadi\n  | author2 = Photos by Lyn Ong\n  | title = Where I\u2019m Coming From: Saifuddin Abdullah\n  | publisher = POPfolio network : Poskod.MY \n  | date = \n  | url = https://poskod.my/features/where-im-coming-from-saifuddin-abdullah/\n  | accessdate = 22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSaifuddin was educated at Sekolah Kebangsaan Abu Bakar Mentakab (1968\u201373), [[Malay College Kuala Kangsar]] - MCKK (1974\u201380), obtained BA Honors from [[University of Malaya]] (1984), Diploma in Translation from Malaysian Translator Association / [[Dewan Bahasa dan Pustaka]] (1985) and followed by the Executive Course at [[Harvard Business School]] (1995).\n\n==Political career==\nSaifuddin was elected to Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 election]],<ref name=\"The Star 2008 GE results\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia Decides 2008\n  | publisher = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n  | url = http://thestar.com.my/election/\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> and was immediately appointed as a deputy minister,<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Khoo\n |first       = Simon\n |title       = Signs for Pahang to buck up\n |newspaper   = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n |date        = 25 March 2008\n |url         = http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2008/3/25/southneast/20738139&sec=southneast\n |access-date  = 9 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604052750/http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F25%2Fsouthneast%2F20738139&sec=southneast\n |archive-date = 4 June 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> being cited as a future ministerial prospect.<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Koshy\n |first       = Shaila\n |title       = Zaid: Future looks bright although Malaysia faces a lot of problems\n |newspaper   = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n |date        = 8 January 2009\n |url         = http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/1/8/nation/2966514&sec=nation\n |access-date  = 9 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604052821/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2009%2F1%2F8%2Fnation%2F2966514&sec=nation\n |archive-date = 4 June 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He had previously been the Secretary-General of the Malaysian Youth Council.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = Ahmad\n  | first = Abdul Razak\n  | title = Matin tasked with monitoring religious activities\n  | newspaper = [[New Straits Times]]\n  | date = 21 April 2000\n  | url = https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=LtIVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6569,1304733&dq=saifuddin-abdullah&hl=en\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> After the election he was appointed as a deputy minister, and was the [[Ministry of Higher Education (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Higher Education]] in [[Najib Razak]]'s first term as [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]]. During his ministerial tenure, Saifuddin was one of the more moderate and liberal-progressive politicians in Najib's administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/10-things-about-saifuddin-abdullah-moderation-poster-boy|title=10 things about Saifuddin Abdullah, moderation poster boy|last=Chi|first=Melissa|date=23 May 2014|work=[[The Malay Mail]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/after-ge13-some-now-relegated-to-political-wilderness|title=After GE13, some relegated to political wilderness|last=Ng|first=Eileen|date=5 May 2014|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=1 July 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714184824/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/after-ge13-some-now-relegated-to-political-wilderness|archive-date=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He criticised his own government's handling of the [[Bersih 2.0 rally]] in 2011, in which over 1,600 protestors were arrested on the streets of [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/umno-deputy-minister-says-putrajaya-will-lose-moral-ground-with-uuca-appeal/|title=Umno deputy minister says Putrajaya will lose moral ground with UUCA appeal|last=Teoh|first=Shannon|date=5 November 2011|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=5 November 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106192820/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/umno-deputy-minister-says-putrajaya-will-lose-moral-ground-with-uuca-appeal|archive-date=6 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early 2013, he also stood up for a student who was humiliated by a government-linked panellist at a student forum at the [[Universiti Utara Malaysia]] (UUM).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/01/15/Netizens-give-listen-listen-UUM-speaker-an-earful/|title=Netizens give \"listen, listen\" UUM speaker an earful|date=15 January 2013|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nSaifuddin's ministerial career was cut short by the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]], when he lost his parliamentary seat to a [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) candidate by 1,070 votes.\n\nSaifuddin has written four books on Malaysian politics.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | title = Calling for a new breed of politicians\n  | newspaper = [[Malaysia Today]]\n  | date = 16 March 2009\n  | url = http://mt.m2day.org/2008/content/view/19244/84/\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> After leaving Parliament he joined the [[University of Malaya]] as a research fellow, but in 2014, he resigned his position in protest when Malaysia's Education Ministry forced a well-respected professor at the university to resign, reportedly due to research findings critical of the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.astroawani.com/news/show/saifuddin-quits-um-post-in-solidarity-with-umcedel-director-38746|title=Saifuddin quits UM post in solidarity with UMcedel director|last=Awani|first=Astro|date=30 June 2014|work=Astro Awani|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/06/30/Saifuddin-quits-as-UM-fellow/|title=Saifuddin quits as UM fellow in solidarity with dismissed Prof Redzuan|last=Suganya|first=L.|date=29 June 2014|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Saifuddin quit UMNO and joined the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) over disagreements with the government's handling of the [[1Malaysia Development Berhad scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/i-left-umno-over-1mdb-rm2.6-billion-says-saifuddin|title=I left Umno over 1MDB, RM2.6 billion, says Saifuddin|last=Ng|first=Eileen|date=15 October 2015|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015190255/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/i-left-umno-over-1mdb-rm2.6-billion-says-saifuddin|archive-date=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/10/25/saifuddin-gives-his-reasons-datuk-saifuddin-abdullah-explains-why-he-left-umno-after-almost-three-de/|title=Saifuddin gives his reasons for leaving Umno|last=|first=|date=25 October 2015|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Saifuddin quit PKR along with deputy president [[Azmin Ali]] and 9 other MP's to form an independent parliamentary block.<ref name=\"azminquit\">{{cite news |title=Azmin quits PKR, takes 10 other MPs with him |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/512030 |accessdate=24 February 2020 |agency=Malaysiakini |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"The Star 2008 GE results\"/><ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web  | title = Malaysia General Election   | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]  | url = http://undi.info/#  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name =\"myundi pru 13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |title=my undi : Kawasan & Calon-Calon PRU13 : Keputusan PRU13 (Archived copy) |website=www.myundi.com.my|access-date=2014-04-09 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331000718/http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |archive-date=31 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Utusan PRU 13 results\">{{cite web|url=http://ww2.utusan.com.my/utusan/special.asp?pr=PilihanRaya2013&pg=keputusan.htm|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum ke-13|work=[[Utusan Malaysia]]|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> \n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots<br />cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|rowspan=2 |'''P088 [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]], Pahang'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Saifuddin Abdullah'''}} ([[United Malay National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''21,381'''\n|'''53.03%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Ahmad Nizam Hamid ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |18,940\n|46.97%\n|41,463\n|2,441\n|76.77%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Saifuddin Abdullah ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |27,197\n|49.04%\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|'''Nasrudin Hassan''' ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|'''PAS''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''28,267'''\n|'''50.96%'''\n|56,595\n|1,070\n|85.61%\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=2|'''P082 [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]], Pahang'''\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n| rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''Saifuddin Abdullah'''}} ('''[[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]]''')\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\"|'''28,578'''\n| rowspan=2|'''44.85%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|Johan Mat Sah}} ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |17,628\n|27.66%\n| rowspan=2|64,612\n| rowspan=2|10,950\n| rowspan=2|83.70%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Nasrudin Hassan}} ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |17,515\n|27.49%\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Pahang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PAH Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang - Knight Companion - DSAP.svg|50px]] Knight Companion of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang]] (DSAP) - '''Dato'''' (2009)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|publisher=[[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)]]|accessdate=24 October 2018|title=SEMAKAN PENERIMA DARJAH KEBESARAN, BINTANG DAN PINGAT}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/10/24/1114-to-receive-pahang-honours/|date=24 October 2009|accessdate=24 October 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=1,114 to receive Pahang honours}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Perak}} :\n** [[File:MY-PERA Order of the Perak State Crown - lower classes.svg|50px]] Knight Commander of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Perak|Order of the Perak State Crown]] (DPMP) - '''Dato'''' (2002)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{Pahang-FedRep}}\n{{Seventh Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Pakatan Harapan}}\n{{ASEAN Foreign}}\n{{APEC Foreign Ministers}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\u2190\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdullah, Saifuddin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Pahang]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Malay name|Saifuddin|Abdullah}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']]\n| name = Saifuddin Abdullah\n| native_name = \u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|DSAP]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Perak|DPMP]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]}}\n| image = Secretary Pompeo Meets with Malaysian FM Saifuddin Abdullah (42012332590) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Abdullah in 2018\n| birth_name = Saifuddin bin Abdullah\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|01|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Kampung Sungai Ara, [[Mentakab]], [[Pahang]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = [[Minister of Communications and Multimedia (Malaysia)|Minister of Communications and Multimedia]]\n| term_start = 10 March 2020\n| term_end = \n| primeminister = [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]\n| deputy = [[Zahidi Zainul Abidin]]\n| predecessor = [[Gobind Singh Deo]]\n| successor   = \n| constituency = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| monarch = [[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| office4 = Chief Secretary of [[Pakatan Harapan]]\n| 1blankname4 = Chairman\n| 1namedata4 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| leader4 = [[Anwar Ibrahim]]\n| president4 = [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]]\n| term_start4 = 19 October 2015\n| term_end4 = 24 February 2020\n| predecessor4 = ''Position established''\n| successor4  = [[Saifuddin Nasution Ismail]]\n| constituency4 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| office1 = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start1 = 2 July 2018\n| term_end1 = 24 February 2020\n| primeminister1 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| deputy1 = [[Marzuki Yahya]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Anifah Aman]]\n| successor1   = [[Hishammuddin Hussein]]\n| constituency1 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| monarch1 = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Higher Education II]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Najib Razak]]\n| alongside2 = [[Hou Kok Chung]]\n| minister2 = [[Mohamed Khaled Nordin]]\n| constituency2 = [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Idris Haron]]\n| successor2 = [[Mary Yap Kain Ching]] {{small|as Deputy Minister of Education}} \n| monarch2 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]\n| term_start2 = 10 April 2009\n| term_end2 = 15 May 2013\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Entrepreneur and Co-operatives Development]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| minister3 = [[Noh Omar]]\n| constituency3 = Temerloh\n| predecessor3 = Khamsiyah Yeop\n| successor3 = [[Tan Lian Hoe]] {{small|as Deputy Minister of Domestic Trade, Co-operatives and Consumerism}}\n| monarch3 = Mizan Zainal Abidin\n| term_start3 = 19 March 2008\n| term_end3 = 9 April 2009\n| term_start5 = 9 May 2018\n| term_end5 =\n| constituency_MP5 = [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]\n| parliament5 = Malaysian\n| majority5 = 10,950 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor5 = [[Fauzi Abdul Rahman]] ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n| successor5 =\n| constituency_MP6 = [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]]\n| parliament6 = Malaysian\n| term_start6 = 8 March 2008\n| term_end6 = 5 May 2013\n| majority6 = 2,441 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])\n| predecessor6 = Mohd Sarit Yusoh ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]]) \n| successor6 = Nasrudin Hassan ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| party = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) {{small|(until 2015)}}<br />[[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2015-2020)}} <br/>[[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] (PPBM) (since 2020)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations =\n| spouse = Datin Norlin Shamsul Bahri\n| children = 1\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.saifuddinabdullah.com.my/}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']] '''Saifuddin bin Abdullah''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0633\u064a\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647; born 27 January 1961) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and [[Minister of Communications and Multimedia (Malaysia)|Minister of Communications and Multimedia]] and the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]]. He is also a member of the ruling [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition. Previously, he was the Member of [[Parliament of Malaysia]] for the [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]] constituency in [[Pahang]] from 2008 to 2013 representing [[United Malay National Organisation]] (UMNO), the leading party in the then-ruling coalition of [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN).\n\n==Personal life==\nSaifuddin was born to an [[Ustad|ustaz]] father and a schoolteacher mother in [[Temerloh]] near [[Mentakab]], Pahang.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | author1 = Interview by Abdul Qayyum Jumadi\n  | author2 = Photos by Lyn Ong\n  | title = Where I\u2019m Coming From: Saifuddin Abdullah\n  | publisher = POPfolio network : Poskod.MY \n  | date = \n  | url = https://poskod.my/features/where-im-coming-from-saifuddin-abdullah/\n  | accessdate = 22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSaifuddin was educated at Sekolah Kebangsaan Abu Bakar Mentakab (1968\u201373), [[Malay College Kuala Kangsar]] - MCKK (1974\u201380), obtained BA Honors from [[University of Malaya]] (1984), Diploma in Translation from Malaysian Translator Association / [[Dewan Bahasa dan Pustaka]] (1985) and followed by the Executive Course at [[Harvard Business School]] (1995).\n\n==Political career==\nSaifuddin was elected to Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 election]],<ref name=\"The Star 2008 GE results\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia Decides 2008\n  | publisher = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n  | url = http://thestar.com.my/election/\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> and was immediately appointed as a deputy minister,<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Khoo\n |first       = Simon\n |title       = Signs for Pahang to buck up\n |newspaper   = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n |date        = 25 March 2008\n |url         = http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2008/3/25/southneast/20738139&sec=southneast\n |access-date  = 9 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604052750/http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F25%2Fsouthneast%2F20738139&sec=southneast\n |archive-date = 4 June 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> being cited as a future ministerial prospect.<ref>{{Cite news\n |last        = Koshy\n |first       = Shaila\n |title       = Zaid: Future looks bright although Malaysia faces a lot of problems\n |newspaper   = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]\n |date        = 8 January 2009\n |url         = http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2009/1/8/nation/2966514&sec=nation\n |access-date  = 9 January 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604052821/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2009%2F1%2F8%2Fnation%2F2966514&sec=nation\n |archive-date = 4 June 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He had previously been the Secretary-General of the Malaysian Youth Council.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = Ahmad\n  | first = Abdul Razak\n  | title = Matin tasked with monitoring religious activities\n  | newspaper = [[New Straits Times]]\n  | date = 21 April 2000\n  | url = https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=LtIVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6569,1304733&dq=saifuddin-abdullah&hl=en\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> After the election he was appointed as a deputy minister, and was the [[Ministry of Higher Education (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Higher Education]] in [[Najib Razak]]'s first term as [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]]. During his ministerial tenure, Saifuddin was one of the more moderate and liberal-progressive politicians in Najib's administration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/10-things-about-saifuddin-abdullah-moderation-poster-boy|title=10 things about Saifuddin Abdullah, moderation poster boy|last=Chi|first=Melissa|date=23 May 2014|work=[[The Malay Mail]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/after-ge13-some-now-relegated-to-political-wilderness|title=After GE13, some relegated to political wilderness|last=Ng|first=Eileen|date=5 May 2014|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=1 July 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714184824/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/after-ge13-some-now-relegated-to-political-wilderness|archive-date=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He criticised his own government's handling of the [[Bersih 2.0 rally]] in 2011, in which over 1,600 protestors were arrested on the streets of [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/umno-deputy-minister-says-putrajaya-will-lose-moral-ground-with-uuca-appeal/|title=Umno deputy minister says Putrajaya will lose moral ground with UUCA appeal|last=Teoh|first=Shannon|date=5 November 2011|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=5 November 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106192820/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/umno-deputy-minister-says-putrajaya-will-lose-moral-ground-with-uuca-appeal|archive-date=6 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early 2013, he also stood up for a student who was humiliated by a government-linked panellist at a student forum at the [[Universiti Utara Malaysia]] (UUM).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/01/15/Netizens-give-listen-listen-UUM-speaker-an-earful/|title=Netizens give \"listen, listen\" UUM speaker an earful|date=15 January 2013|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nSaifuddin's ministerial career was cut short by the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]], when he lost his parliamentary seat to a [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) candidate by 1,070 votes.\n\nSaifuddin has written four books on Malaysian politics.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | title = Calling for a new breed of politicians\n  | newspaper = [[Malaysia Today]]\n  | date = 16 March 2009\n  | url = http://mt.m2day.org/2008/content/view/19244/84/\n  | accessdate = 9 January 2010}}</ref> After leaving Parliament he joined the [[University of Malaya]] as a research fellow, but in 2014, he resigned his position in protest when Malaysia's Education Ministry forced a well-respected professor at the university to resign, reportedly due to research findings critical of the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.astroawani.com/news/show/saifuddin-quits-um-post-in-solidarity-with-umcedel-director-38746|title=Saifuddin quits UM post in solidarity with UMcedel director|last=Awani|first=Astro|date=30 June 2014|work=Astro Awani|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/06/30/Saifuddin-quits-as-UM-fellow/|title=Saifuddin quits as UM fellow in solidarity with dismissed Prof Redzuan|last=Suganya|first=L.|date=29 June 2014|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Saifuddin quit UMNO and joined the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) over disagreements with the government's handling of the [[1Malaysia Development Berhad scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/i-left-umno-over-1mdb-rm2.6-billion-says-saifuddin|title=I left Umno over 1MDB, RM2.6 billion, says Saifuddin|last=Ng|first=Eileen|date=15 October 2015|work=[[The Malaysian Insider]]|access-date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015190255/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/i-left-umno-over-1mdb-rm2.6-billion-says-saifuddin|archive-date=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/10/25/saifuddin-gives-his-reasons-datuk-saifuddin-abdullah-explains-why-he-left-umno-after-almost-three-de/|title=Saifuddin gives his reasons for leaving Umno|last=|first=|date=25 October 2015|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Saifuddin quit PKR along with deputy president [[Azmin Ali]] and 9 other MP's to form an independent parliamentary block.<ref name=\"azminquit\">{{cite news |title=Azmin quits PKR, takes 10 other MPs with him |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/512030 |accessdate=24 February 2020 |agency=Malaysiakini |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"The Star 2008 GE results\"/><ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web  | title = Malaysia General Election   | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]  | url = http://undi.info/#  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name =\"myundi pru 13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |title=my undi : Kawasan & Calon-Calon PRU13 : Keputusan PRU13 (Archived copy) |website=www.myundi.com.my|access-date=2014-04-09 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331000718/http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |archive-date=31 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Utusan PRU 13 results\">{{cite web|url=http://ww2.utusan.com.my/utusan/special.asp?pr=PilihanRaya2013&pg=keputusan.htm|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum ke-13|work=[[Utusan Malaysia]]|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> \n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots<br />cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|rowspan=2 |'''P088 [[Temerloh (federal constituency)|Temerloh]], Pahang'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Saifuddin Abdullah'''}} ([[United Malay National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''21,381'''\n|'''53.03%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Ahmad Nizam Hamid ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |18,940\n|46.97%\n|41,463\n|2,441\n|76.77%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Saifuddin Abdullah ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |27,197\n|49.04%\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|'''Nasrudin Hassan''' ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|'''PAS''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''28,267'''\n|'''50.96%'''\n|56,595\n|1,070\n|85.61%\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=2|'''P082 [[Indera Mahkota (federal constituency)|Indera Mahkota]], Pahang'''\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} | \n| rowspan=2|{{nowrap|'''Saifuddin Abdullah'''}} ('''[[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]]''')\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\"|'''28,578'''\n| rowspan=2|'''44.85%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|Johan Mat Sah}} ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]])\n|align=\"right\" |17,628\n|27.66%\n| rowspan=2|64,612\n| rowspan=2|10,950\n| rowspan=2|83.70%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Nasrudin Hassan}} ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |17,515\n|27.49%\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Pahang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PAH Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang - Knight Companion - DSAP.svg|50px]] Knight Companion of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|Order of Sultan Ahmad Shah of Pahang]] (DSAP) - '''Dato'''' (2009)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|publisher=[[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)]]|accessdate=24 October 2018|title=SEMAKAN PENERIMA DARJAH KEBESARAN, BINTANG DAN PINGAT}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/10/24/1114-to-receive-pahang-honours/|date=24 October 2009|accessdate=24 October 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=1,114 to receive Pahang honours}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Perak}} :\n** [[File:MY-PERA Order of the Perak State Crown - lower classes.svg|50px]] Knight Commander of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Perak|Order of the Perak State Crown]] (DPMP) - '''Dato'''' (2002)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{Pahang-FedRep}}\n{{Seventh Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Pakatan Harapan}}\n{{ASEAN Foreign}}\n{{APEC Foreign Ministers}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\u2190\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdullah, Saifuddin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Pahang]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saifuddin_Abdullah"}
{"title_page": "Abdullah Sani Abdul Hamid", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Malay name|Abdullah Sani|Abdul Hamid}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']]\n| name = Abdullah Sani Abdul Hamid\n| native_name = \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0633\u0646\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u064a\u062f\n| honorific-suffix = [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|DSPN]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Negeri Sembilan|DSNS]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Negeri Sembilan|DPTJ]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|02|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Perak]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency_MP = [[Kapar (federal constituency)|Kapar]]\n| parliament = Malaysian\n| term_start = 9 May 2018\n| term_end = \n| majority = 16,306 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor = [[Manivannan Gowindasamy]] ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\t\n| successor =\n| constituency_MP1 = [[Kuala Langat (federal constituency)|Kuala Langat]]\n| parliament1 = Malaysian\n| term_start1 = 8 March 2008\n| term_end1 = 9 May 2018\n| majority1 = 989 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />5,358 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])\n| predecessor1 = [[Shafie Salleh]] ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor1 = [[Xavier Jayakumar Arulanandam]] ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\t\n| party = [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| occupation = Politician, Trade-unionist\n| nationality = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']] '''Abdullah Sani bin Abdul Hamid''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0633\u0646\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u064a\u062f; born 15 February 1962) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for the [[Kapar]] constituency in [[Selangor]]. He is a member of the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) ruling coalition. He was the MP for the [[Kuala Langat (federal constituency)|Kuala Langat]] constituency previously from 2008 to 2018.\n\nBorn in Perak, and with a background as a trade unionist,<ref name=\"Kandiah\">{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/kuala-langat-indians-to-decide-the-winner |title=Kuala Langat: Indians to decide the winner |last=Kandiah |first=Sugasini |date=5 January 2013 |work=The Malaysian Insider |accessdate=18 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018113250/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/kuala-langat-indians-to-decide-the-winner |archivedate=18 October 2014 }}</ref> Abdullah Sani was elected to Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]], narrowly winning the seat of Kuala Langat from the ruling [[Barisan Nasional]] coalition. He was re-elected in the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]] with an increased margin.<ref name=\"2008 election results\">{{Cite web\n |title=Malaysia Decides 2008 \n |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)]] \n |url=http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |accessdate=18 January 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409212729/http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |archivedate=9 April 2008 \n}}</ref> In 2013 he also won election as deputy president of the [[Malaysian Trades Union Congress]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2013/12/22/mtuc-elections/|title=Incumbent MTUC president Mohd Khalid retains post|last=Lee|first=Patrick|date=22 December 2013|work=The Star|accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref> He was a prominent player in the 2014 [[Kajang Move]], an internal PKR machination to oust Selangor's Chief Minister, and PKR member, [[Khalid Ibrahim]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/03/PKR-reps-want-MB-out-Move-to-get-Khalid-to-resign-hots-up-among-party-members/|title=PKR reps want MB out|last=Wani Muthiah|author2=Loh Foon Fong|date=3 August 2014|work=The Star|accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref> He is also a member of the Central Leadership Council of PKR.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keadilanrakyat.org/leaders/pusat/majlis-pimpinan-pusat/ |title=Majlis Pimpinan Pusat |website=Parti Keadilan Rakyat |access-date=31 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318160838/http://www.keadilanrakyat.org/leaders/pusat/majlis-pimpinan-pusat/ |archivedate=18 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Abdullah Sani contested and won the Kapar parliamentary seat.\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\" \n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"2008 election results\"/><ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=6 June 2010 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"GE13 results\"