decessor2 = [[Lajim Ukin]]\n| minister2 = [[Ong Tee Keat]] (2009-2010)<br />[[Kong Cho Ha]] (2010-2013)\n| monarch2 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />Abdul Halim\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| constituency3 = Kudat\n| term_start3 = 19 March 2008\n| term_end3 = 9 April 2009\n| successor3 = 1. A. Kohillan Pillay<br />2. [[Lee Chee Leong]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Joseph Salang Gandum]]\n| minister3 = [[Rais Yatim]]\n| monarch3 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />Abdul Halim\n| constituency_MP4 = [[Kudat (federal constituency)|Kudat]]\n| parliament4 = Malaysian\n| term_start4 = 2004\n| term_end4 =\n| majority4 = 6,748 ([[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]])<br />9,895 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />12,376 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />1,359 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor4 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor4 =\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = Malaysian United Indigenous Party (2019-present)<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018-2019)<br />[[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]] (until 2018)\n| otherparty = [[Perikatan Nasional]] (PN) (2020-present) <br/>[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) (2019-2020)<br />[[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (until 2018)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]] [[Hajji|Haji]] '''Abdul Rahim bin Bakri''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0631\u062d\u064a\u0645 \u0628\u0646 \u0628\u0643\u0631\u064a; born 11 April 1961) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician, and currently serving as Deputy Minister of Finances I since 10 March 2020. He is the [[Member of Parliament]] of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for the [[Kudat (federal constituency)|Kudat]] constituency in [[Sabah]], presently representing the [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] (BERSATU) from 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/15/six-sabah-reps-who-jumped-from-umno-get-bersatu-cards/|title=Six Sabah reps who jumped from Umno get Bersatu cards|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author= Mazwin Nik Anis and Joseph Kaos Jr|date=15 March 2019|access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref> He had earlier left [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) in the opposition [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition to become an [[Independent politician|Independent]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/12/sabah-umno-exodus-begins-with-nine-of-10-assemblymen-leaving-party/|title=Sabah Umno exodus sees nine of 10 Aduns, five of six MPs leave|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Muguntan Vanar, Stephanie Lee and Natasha Joibi|date=12 December 2018|access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAbdul Rahim was elected to federal Parliament in the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 general elections]].<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=18 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout (including votes for candidates not listed).</ref> Since 2008 he had been a deputy minister in the former ruling [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) government until 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlimen.gov.my/index.php?modload=ahlidewan&uweb=dr&action=details&id=161|title=Abdul Rahim bin Bakri, Y.B. Datuk Haji|publisher=[[Parliament of Malaysia]]|accessdate=11 March 2010}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019}}</ref> In April 2008, he was appointed as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/04/19/deputy-ministers-chosen/|title=Deputy ministers chosen|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=19 April 2008|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref> and was appointed [[Ministry of Transport (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Transport]] in April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsgeneral.php?id=402979|title=Najib Announces 28-member Cabinet|publisher=[[Bernama]]|date=9 April 2008|accessdate=11 March 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622072113/http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsgeneral.php?id=402979|archivedate=22 June 2011|url-status=dead}} {{subscription required}}</ref> He was again moved, this time being appointed as the [[Ministry of Defence (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Defence]], after the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abnxcess.com/2013/05/the-complete-list-of-ministers-and-deputy-ministers-in-najibs-new-cabinet/|title=The complete list of Ministers and Deputy Ministers in Najib\u2019s new Cabinet|publisher=ABN News|date=15 May 2013|accessdate=3 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102160258/http://news.abnxcess.com/2013/05/the-complete-list-of-ministers-and-deputy-ministers-in-najibs-new-cabinet/|archivedate=2 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Election results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P167 [[Kudat (federal constituency)|Kudat]], Sabah<ref name=\"election results\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/sabah.html|title=Sabah [Parliament Results]|publisher=The Star|accessdate=18 May 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517234741/https://election.thestar.com.my/sabah.html|archivedate=18 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Abdul Rahim Bakri'''}} ([[United Malays National Org