ources]]\n| term_end3 = 26 March 2004\n| term_start3 = 15 December 1999\n| minister3 = [[Fong Chan Onn]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]<br />Abdullah Ahmad Badawi\n| predecessor3 = Affifudin Omar\n| successor3 = Abdul Rahman Bakar\n| constituency3 = Mersing\n| monarch3 = [[Salahuddin of Selangor|Salahuddin]]<br />Sirajuddin\n| constituency_MP4 = [[Mersing (federal constituency)|Mersing]]\n| parliament4 = Malaysian\n| term_start4 = 1999\n| term_end4 =\n| majority4 = 10,861 ([[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]])<br />14,573 ([[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]])<br />13,736 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />15,747 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />8,459 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| predecessor4 = Zainal Abidin Osman ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor4 =\n| office5 = Chairman of [[Syarikat Perumahan Negara Berhad]] (SPNB)\n| term_start5 = 11 June 2013\n| term_end5 = 30 January 2019\n| minister5 = [[Najib Razak]]\n| 1blankname5 = [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]]\n| 1namedata5 = Ahmad Azizi Ali\n| predecessor5 = [[Idris Haron]]\n| successor5 = Mohammad Mentek \n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party|PPBM]] (2019-present)<br /> [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018-2019)<br />[[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]] (until 2018)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) (2019-present)<br />[[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (until 2018)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| website =\n| footnotes = {{facebook|abdullatiff.ahmad.9}}<br>{{pom|3678}}\n}}\n\n'''Abdul Latiff bin Ahmad''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0637\u064a\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f ; born 9 July 1958) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] and is the incumbent [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for the [[Mersing (federal constituency)|Mersing]] constituency in the [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|state]] of [[Johor]] for fifth term since 1999.<ref name=\"election results\">{{Cite web\n |title=Malaysia Decides 2008 \n |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)]] \n |publisher=Star Publications (Malaysia) \n |url=http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |accessdate=28 January 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409212729/http://thestar.com.my/election/ \n |archivedate=9 April 2008 \n}} Percentage figures are calculated based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"election results 2\">{{Cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | author2 =\n  | title = Malaysia General Election\n  | work =undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher =[[Malaysiakini]]\n  | date =\n  | url = http://undi.info/johor/\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =11 March 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"election results 3\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |accessdate=17 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906083741/http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |archivedate=6 September 2011 |df=dmy }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> He was a member of the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO); a component party of [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition. He resigned from UMNO to be an [[Independent politician]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/15/six-more-mps-leave-umno-latest-exodus-leaves-party-with-only-37-lawmakers-in-dewan-rakyat/|title=Six more MPs leave Umno|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Mazwin Nik Anis, Muguntan Vanar and Zakiah Koya|date=15 December 2018|access-date=15 December 2018}}</ref> Presently he is a member of the [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] or ''Parti Pribumi Bersatu Malaysia'' (BERSATU), a component of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition since 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/02/12/seven-umno-mps-join-bersatu/|title=Seven Umno MPs join Bersatu|publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author=Mazwin Nik Anis and Joseph Kaos Jr|date=12 February 2019|access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAbdul Latiff was firstly elected to the [[Johor State Legislative Assembly]] for [[Endau]] seat in [[1995 Malaysian state elections|1995 election]]. In the [[1999 Malaysian general election|1999 general election]] he switched to federal politics by contesting and winning to be the MP of Mersing constituency in Johor, and thereafter served as [[Ministry of Human Resources (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Human Resources]] (1999 to 2004), [[Ministry of Health (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Health]] (2004 to 2010) and [[Ministry of Defence (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Defence]] (2010 to 2013). He was reelected MP for the Mersing parliamentary seat in the consecutive [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]], [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]], [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]] and [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]] general elections.\n\nAbdul Latiff was dropped from [[Najib Razak]]'s cabinet after the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]], and was appointed as the chairman of the government-linked housing development company [[Syarikat Perumahan Negara Berhad]] (SPNB).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/former-deputy-minister-dr-abdul-latif-now-spnb-chairman |title=Former deputy minister Dr Abdul Latif now SPNB chairman |date=14 June 2013 |work=The Malaysian Insider |accessdate=2 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101065308/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/former-deputy-minister-dr-abdul-latif-now-spnb-chairman |archivedate=1 November 2014 }}</ref> He left SPNB in early 2019 after BN lost as the ruling federal government to [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/436865 |title=Heads to roll from more than 100 MOF Inc firms, says report |date=1 August 2018 |work=[[Malaysiakini]] |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.utusan.com.my/berita/nasional/mohammad-mentek-dilantik-pengerusi-spnb-1.846237|title=Mohammad Mentek dilantik Pengerusi SPNB|date=22 February 2019|language=Malay|author=Nabila Yasmin Razib |publisher=[[Utusan Malaysia]] |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Johor State Legislative Assembly]]'''<ref name=\"election results 3\"/>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government  \n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1995 Malaysian state elections|1995]]\n|N9 [[Endau]], P129 Mersing.\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''7,315'''\n|'''69%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Sheikh Abdullah Said Salleh ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |3,302\n|31%\n|10,668\t \n|4,013\n|64.36%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"election results\"/><ref name=\"election results 2\"/><ref name=\"election results 3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/johor.html|title=14th General Election Malaysia (GE14 / PRU14) - Johor|website=election.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref><ref>https://undi.info/johor/r18/p154</ref> \n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|P129 [[Mersing (federal constituency)|Mersing]], Johor.\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ('''[[UMNO]]''')\n|align=\"right\" |'''18,821'''\n|'''70.28%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Idris Tukachil ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |7,960\n|29.72%\n|27,617\n|10,861\n|70.29%\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|rowspan=5|P154 [[Mersing (federal constituency)|Mersing]], Johor.\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ('''[[UMNO]]''')\n|align=\"right\" |'''19,222'''\n|'''80.52%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Idris Tukachil ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,649\n|19.48%\n|24,484\n|14,573\n|72.25%\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ('''[[UMNO]]''')\n|align=\"right\" |'''20,116'''\n|'''75.92%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Shahar Abdullah ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |6,380\n|24.08%\n|27,548\n|13,736\n|75.59%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''26,184'''\n|'''71.50%'''\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Roslan Nikmat ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |10,437\n|28.50%\n|37,393\n|15,747\n|84.03%\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n| rowspan=2|'''Abdul Latiff Ahmad''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n| rowspan=2 align=\"right\"|'''19,806'''\n| rowspan=2|'''53.00%'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|Md Nasir Hashim ([[Malaysian United Indigenous Party|PPBM]])\n|align=\"right\" |11,347\n|30.37%\n| rowspan=2|38,306\n| rowspan=2|8,459\n| rowspan=2|79.51%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|A. Rahman A. Hamid ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |6,215\n|16.63%\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Honours of Malaysia===\n* {{Flag|Malacca}} :\n** [[File:MY-MAL Exalted Order of Malacca.svg|50px]] Companion Class I of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Malacca)|Order of Malacca]] (DMSM) - '''Datuk''' (2003)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=11 October 2018|date=12 October 2003|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/10/12/the-malacca-yang-dipertua-negris-birthday-honours-list/|title=The Malacca Yang Di-Pertua Negri's Birthday Honours List}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Johor-FedRep}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdul Latiff Ahmad}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Johor]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian United Indigenous Party politicians]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdul_Latiff_Ahmad"}
{"title_page": "Hassan Abdul Karim", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian lawyer and politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Malay name|Hassan|Abdul Karim|note=on}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n|honorific_suffix = {{small|[[Member of parliament|MP]]}}\n|native_name = \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645\n|image = \n|caption =\n\n|office = 5th President of [[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Party]]\n|term_start = 17 April 2005\n|term_end = 17 November 2009\n|predecessor = [[Syed Husin Ali]]\n|successor = Ariffin Salimon (''Acting'')<br />Rohana Ariffin\n|deputy = S. K. Song\n\n|office2 = Chair of the [[Federal-State Relations Select Committee]]\n|predecessor2 = ''Office established''\n|successor2 = \n|term_start2 = 4 December 2018\n|term_end2 =\n\n|constituency_MP3 = [[Pasir Gudang (federal constituency)|Pasir Gudang]]\n|majority3 = 24,726 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n|term_start3 = 10 May 2018\n|term_end3 = \n|successor3 = \n|parliament3 = Malaysian\n|predecessor3 = [[Normala Abdul Samad]] ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n\n|birth_name = Hassan bin Abdul Karim\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1951}}\n|birth_place = {{where|date=June 2019}}[[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|party = [[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Party]] (PRM) {{small|(1978\u20132009)}}<br />[[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2009\u2013present)}}\n|otherparty = [[Barisan Alternatif]] (BA) {{small|(1998\u20132004)}}<br />[[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR) {{small|(2009\u20132015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n|alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]<br />[[University of London]]\n|nationality = {{MAS}}\n|citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n|residence = Pontian Besar, [[Pontian District|Pontian]], Johor, Malaysia\n|occupation = Politician\n|profession = Lawyer\n|relations =\n|spouse = \n|children = \n|website =\n|footnotes = {{facebook|hassankarim2013}}<br>{{pom|3684}}\n}}\n\n'''Hassan bin Abdul Karim''' (born 1951; [[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician. He is currently serving as [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Pasir Gudang (federal constituency)|Pasir Gudang]] constituency in Johor representing the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR), a component party of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition since 2018. He was formerly the president of [[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|Malaysian People's Party]] (PRM).\n\n==Political career==\nHassan, a lawyer by profession,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/05/02/pkr-pasir-gudang-voters-more-welcoming-this-time-around/|title=PKR: Pasir Gudang voters more welcoming this time around|accessdate=2 May 2018|work=V Anbalagan|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=23 November 2009}}</ref> joined PRM in 1978 before rising to become its youth chief.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2005/04/17/lonely-crusade-to-revive-prm|title=Lonely crusade to revive PRM|date=17 April 2005 |work=JOCELINE TAN|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> In April 2005, Hassan was elected president of PRM by party members who were against the party's merger with the [[National Justice Party]] into the [[People's Justice Party]] (PKR).<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/11/23/prm-chief-joins-pkr/|title=PRM chief joins PKR|accessdate=4 May 2019|work=Sira Habibu|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=23 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the party's rejection of Hassan's proposal for the party to enter into the [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR) opposition coalition during a party congress, he announced his intention to resign on 15 November 2009. Hassan then joined PKR later in the month, which was a component party of the PR coalition.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nIn the [[Malaysian general election, 2018|2018 Malaysian general election]], Hassan contested as a candidate for the [[Pasir Gudang (federal constituency)|Pasir Gudang]] parliamentary seat against the then-[[Menteri Besar of Johor]], [[Mohamed Khaled Nordin]] in a four cornered-fight and was able to win the seat with a majority of 24,726 votes. On 4 December 2018, Hassan was elected chair of the [[Federal-State Relations Select Committee]], one of the [[Parliamentary Committees of Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Anwar's release from prison and return to the PKR presidency, Hassan was appointed PKR [[Johor]] state chairman in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/456421|work=Andrew Ong |title=Some obscure faces made PKR state chiefs|date=16 December 2018 |publisher=[[Malaysiakini]] |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> However, following multiple allegations of [[nepotism]] due to some of the appointees being allegedly linked to Anwar, Hassan decided to refuse the appointment on 14 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/17/hassan-karim-rejects-johor-pkr-chief-post/ |date=17 December 2018|work=Royce Tan|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Hassan Karim rejects Johor PKR chief post |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref> On 28 December 2018, he bolted and accepted the position.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://m.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/hassan-terima-semula-jawatan-pengerusi-pkr-johor1.814012|work=Muhammad Zikri|publisher=[[Utusan Malaysia]] |language=Malay |title=Hassan terima semula jawatan pengerusi PKR Johor|date=1 January 2019}}</ref> Hassan finally quit the position on 19 July 2019,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/19/hassan-karim-quits-as-pkr-johor-chief/1773103|title=Hassan Karim quits as PKR Johor chief|work= Azril Annuar|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|date=19 July 2019|accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref> citing differences with the [[Istana Bukit Serene|Johor Palace]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/20/anwar-johor-pkr-chief-resigned-over-party-issues-and-spat-with-ruler/1773320|title=Anwar: Johor PKR chief resigned over party issues and spat with ruler|work=Yiswaree Palansamy|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|date=20 July 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/485206|title=Hassan adamant on quitting as Johor PKR chief, admits to differences with palace|work=Lu Wei Hoong|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOn 16 November 2015, Hassan was charged at the Shah Alam Sessions Court with three counts of making seditious statements via his public [[Twitter]] account in which he was alleged to have criticised the [[Selangor Sultanate|Selangor Sultan]] [[Sharafuddin of Selangor|Sharafuddin Idris Shah]] being abroad during [[Kajang Move|Selangor Mentri Besar crisis]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2015/11/16/johor-pkr-leader-sedition/|title=Johor PKR leader pleads not guilty to making seditious statements against Selangor Sultan|work= Firdaous Fadzil|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=16 November 2015|accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref> He was discharged not amounting to an acquittal by the Sessions Court in May 2018, following the prosecution's decision to drop the charges.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/07/27/court-discharges-johor-pkr-chief-over-charge-related-to-tweets-on-sultan/|title=Court discharges Johor PKR chief over charge related to tweets on sultan|work=|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=27 July 2018|accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref> On 10 May 2019, he was finally granted a full acquittal on the sedition charges by the Shah Alam High Court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/475702|title=Pasir Gudang MP wins full acquittal on sedition charges|work=Ng Xiang Yi|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|date=11 May 2019|accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1986 Malaysian general election|1986]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |'''[[Tebrau (federal constituency)|Tebrau]]'''\n|{{Party shading/red}} |\n|{{nowrap|Hassan Abdul Karim}} ([[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|PSRM]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|16,085\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|37.21%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Siti Zainabon Abu Bakar''' ('''[[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]]''')\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''27,138'''\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''62.79%'''\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|45,497\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|11,053\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|69.78%\n|-\n|[[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]]\n|{{Party shading/red}} |\n|{{nowrap|Hassan Abdul Karim}} ([[Parti Rakyat Malaysia|PRM]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|13,799\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|21.87%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Mohd. Ali Hassan''' ('''[[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]]''')\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''49,284'''\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''78.13%'''\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|65,572\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|35,485\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|75.19%\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|'''[[Pontian (federa